      <section class="section-block">
        <div class="container">
          <p class="section-question">How do you minimize your digital footprint for crypto privacy?</p>
          <h2 id="a-footprint" >Digital Footprint Minimization</h2>
          <div class="guide-text">
            <p>Every piece of public information about your crypto holdings <strong>increases your attack surface</strong>. Advanced OpSec involves systematically reducing the data trail that connects your identity to your funds.</p>
            <h3>Identity Segregation</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>Use <strong>separate email addresses</strong> for crypto accounts, never linked to your real name or primary email</li>
              <li>Use <strong>unique usernames</strong> for crypto-related forums and social media &mdash; never reuse identifiers from your personal accounts</li>
              <li>Consider <strong>privacy-focused email providers</strong> that don't require phone verification or personal information</li>
              <li>Use a <strong>VPN or Tor</strong> for crypto-related browsing to prevent IP-based correlation</li>
            </ul>
            <h3>Transaction Privacy</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>Never reuse Bitcoin addresses &mdash; use a fresh address for each receive</li>
              <li>Be aware of <strong>chain analysis</strong> &mdash; blockchain transactions are public, and companies specialize in linking addresses to identities</li>
              <li>Use <strong>CoinJoin</strong> or similar privacy-enhancing techniques for Bitcoin transactions when privacy is critical</li>
              <li>Avoid moving funds between KYC-linked exchange addresses and privacy-focused wallets in easily traceable patterns</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="callout callout-tip">
              <span class="callout-label">Pro Tip</span>
              For high-value setups, use a <strong>dedicated device</strong> (phone or laptop) exclusively for crypto operations. This device should never browse the general web, access social media, or install non-essential software. Treat it as a purpose-built secure terminal.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section-block">
        <div class="container">
          <p class="section-question">What is a key ceremony and how do you perform one?</p>
          <h2 id="a-ceremony" >Key Ceremony Procedures</h2>
          <div class="guide-text">
            <p>A <strong>key ceremony</strong> is a deliberate, documented process for generating and storing cryptographic keys. For high-value setups, this should be treated as a formal procedure with defined steps and verification checkpoints.</p>
            <h3>Single-Sig Key Ceremony</h3>
            <ol>
              <li>Prepare a <strong>dedicated offline device</strong> (freshly installed OS or verified hardware wallet firmware)</li>
              <li><strong>Verify wallet software integrity</strong> &mdash; check the binary hash against the developer's signed release, verify GPG signatures</li>
              <li>Conduct generation in a <strong>private, camera-free location</strong></li>
              <li>Generate the seed phrase and <strong>immediately create physical backups</strong> on durable media (<a href="<%= langPrefix %>/">metal plates</a>)</li>
              <li><strong>Verify the backup</strong> &mdash; restore from the written seed on a separate device and confirm the first few addresses match</li>
              <li>Store backups in <strong>separate secure locations</strong> before bringing any device online</li>
              <li><strong>Document the procedure</strong> (without recording the seed) for future reference and inheritance planning</li>
            </ol>
            <h3>Multi-Sig Key Ceremony</h3>
            <p>Multi-sig ceremonies are more complex because each key must be generated independently:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Each key should be generated on a <strong>different device</strong>, ideally from a <strong>different manufacturer</strong></li>
              <li>Key generation should happen in <strong>different physical locations</strong> and ideally by <strong>different individuals</strong></li>
              <li>The <strong>wallet descriptor file</strong> (containing all xpubs and the quorum policy) must be backed up alongside each seed</li>
              <li>Test the multi-sig setup by sending a small amount and <strong>completing a full spend</strong> before committing significant funds</li>
            </ul>
            <blockquote><p>A key ceremony is an investment of time that pays dividends in security confidence. Rushing the process or cutting corners during key generation is where most catastrophic errors originate.</p></blockquote>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section-block">
        <div class="container">
          <p class="section-question">How do you build a multi-layer defense strategy for crypto?</p>
          <h2 id="a-defense" >Multi-Layer Defense Strategy</h2>
          <div class="guide-text">
            <p><strong>Defense in depth</strong> applies multiple independent security layers so an attacker must compromise all of them &mdash; and failure of any single layer does not result in total loss.</p>
            <h3>Security Layer Stack</h3>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Layer 1 &mdash; Device security</strong>: Full-disk encryption, biometric unlock, locked BIOS/firmware, secure boot chain</li>
              <li><strong>Layer 2 &mdash; Authentication</strong>: Strong unique passwords, FIDO2 hardware keys, app-specific 2FA</li>
              <li><strong>Layer 3 &mdash; Isolated signing</strong>: Hardware wallet or air-gapped device &mdash; private keys never on a networked machine</li>
              <li><strong>Layer 4 &mdash; Backup security</strong>: Metal seed plates in geographically separated, access-controlled locations</li>
              <li><strong>Layer 5 &mdash; Passphrase layer</strong>: A BIP39 passphrase (25th word) means the seed alone is insufficient to access funds</li>
              <li><strong>Layer 6 &mdash; Social layer</strong>: Minimizing knowledge of your holdings, using decoy wallets, maintaining a low profile</li>
            </ul>
            <h3>Plausible Deniability</h3>
            <p>A BIP39 passphrase enables the creation of <strong>decoy wallets</strong> through <a href="<%= langPrefix %>/guides/passphrase#b-hidden-wallets">plausible deniability</a>. Your base seed phrase (without passphrase) can lead to a wallet with a small, plausible balance. Your actual holdings exist on a different derivation created by the passphrase. Under coercion, you can reveal the base seed phrase while keeping the passphrase-protected wallet hidden.</p>
            <div class="callout callout-info">
              <span class="callout-label">Duress Planning</span>
              For high-value holders, having a convincing decoy wallet with a moderate balance is a practical countermeasure against physical coercion. The attacker sees a legitimate wallet and has no way to prove additional funds exist elsewhere.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section-block">
        <div class="container">
          <p class="section-question">How do you set up crypto inheritance and dead man's switches?</p>
          <h2 id="a-inheritance" >Inheritance and Dead Man's Switch</h2>
          <div class="guide-text">
            <p><a href="<%= langPrefix %>/guides/self-sovereignty#b-what-is">Self-custody</a> means your heirs cannot simply call a bank or exchange to claim assets. Without explicit planning, your crypto holdings could be <strong>permanently lost</strong> upon your incapacitation or death.</p>
            <h3>Inheritance Planning Approaches</h3>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Letter of instruction</strong> &mdash; a sealed document stored with your will that explains your setup, the location of seed backups, and step-by-step recovery instructions. Written for a technically competent executor.</li>
              <li><strong>Multi-sig inheritance</strong> &mdash; in a 2-of-3 setup, one key is held by a trusted family member, one by a lawyer, and one by yourself. Upon your death, the family member and lawyer can cooperate to access funds.</li>
              <li><strong>Shamir's Secret Sharing</strong> &mdash; SLIP39 shares distributed to multiple heirs/trustees. A threshold of shares can reconstruct the seed after a documented triggering event.</li>
              <li><strong>Timelock contracts</strong> &mdash; on-chain contracts that release funds to a specified address after a certain block height or time, unless periodically "refreshed" by the owner (a dead man's switch).</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="callout callout-warning">
              <span class="callout-label">Critical</span>
              Test your inheritance plan. Have your designated executor (or a trusted proxy) perform a complete mock recovery using your documentation. If they cannot follow the instructions successfully, your heirs will not be able to access the funds when it matters.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section-block">
        <div class="container">
          <p class="section-question">How do you verify wallet software and minimize trust?</p>
          <h2 id="a-verification" >Verification and Trust Minimization</h2>
          <div class="guide-text">
            <p>A core principle of crypto security: <strong>don't trust, verify</strong>. Every piece of software, hardware, and information should be independently verified before you trust it with your keys.</p>
            <h3>Software Verification</h3>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Download from official sources only</strong> &mdash; use the project's official website or verified GitHub repository, never third-party mirrors or app store clones</li>
              <li><strong>Verify checksums</strong> &mdash; compare the SHA-256 hash of downloaded files against the publisher's signed release notes</li>
              <li><strong>Verify GPG signatures</strong> &mdash; confirm the release was signed by the expected developer key</li>
              <li><strong>Reproducible builds</strong> &mdash; for critical software, check if the project supports reproducible builds, allowing you to compile from source and verify it matches the distributed binary</li>
            </ul>
            <h3>Address Verification</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>Always verify the <strong>full address</strong> before sending &mdash; clipboard malware can silently replace the copied address with an attacker's address</li>
              <li>Use your hardware wallet's <strong>trusted display</strong> to confirm the address, not just the computer screen</li>
              <li>For large transfers, <strong>send a small test amount first</strong> and confirm receipt before sending the full amount</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="callout callout-tip">
              <span class="callout-label">Verification Habit</span>
              Make address verification a non-negotiable step in every transaction. Check at least the first 6 and last 6 characters of the address on both your computer screen and your hardware wallet display. This catches both clipboard malware and display-level attacks.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>
    </div>

    <!-- ===== FAQ ===== -->
    <section class="section-block faq-section">
      <div class="container">
        <p class="label">[ FREQUENTLY ASKED QUESTIONS ]</p>
        <h2 >FAQ</h2>
        <div class="faq-chat">

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q-btn" type="button">
              <span>Should I tell people how much crypto I own?</span>
              <span class="faq-arrow">&rsaquo;</span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-bubble-wrap">
              <div class="faq-bubble" data-text="No. Public disclosure of holdings makes you a target for social engineering, phishing, SIM-swap attacks, and even physical coercion. The crypto community principle is: never reveal your portfolio size. Keep holdings private and only discuss specifics with trusted advisors (lawyer, accountant) under appropriate legal confidentiality."></div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q-btn" type="button">
              <span>Is a password manager safe for storing seed phrases?</span>
              <span class="faq-arrow">&rsaquo;</span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-bubble-wrap">
              <div class="faq-bubble" data-text="Password managers are excellent for account passwords and 2FA backup codes, but storing your seed phrase there is risky. If your master password is phished or your device is compromised, the attacker gains access to the seed. Seed phrases should exist only on physical media (stamped metal, hand-written paper) stored in secure offline locations. The principle is clear: seed phrases belong in the physical world, not the digital one."></div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q-btn" type="button">
              <span>What is a &ldquo;$5 wrench attack&rdquo;?</span>
              <span class="faq-arrow">&rsaquo;</span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-bubble-wrap">
              <div class="faq-bubble" data-text="A $5 wrench attack (also called a rubber hose attack) refers to physical coercion &mdash; an attacker uses threats or violence to force you to hand over your keys. No amount of encryption protects against someone who can compel you to reveal your password. Countermeasures include: multi-sig (no single person holds all keys), decoy wallets (reveal a plausible small-balance wallet under duress), geographic distribution of keys, and most importantly &mdash; not advertising your holdings."></div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q-btn" type="button">
              <span>How often should I test my backups?</span>
              <span class="faq-arrow">&rsaquo;</span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-bubble-wrap">
              <div class="faq-bubble" data-text="Test your seed phrase recovery at least once per year and after any major wallet software update or hardware change. Use a separate device, enter the seed phrase, and verify that the first several derived addresses match your known addresses. Never test on a device that holds live funds with significant value. An untested backup is not a backup &mdash; it is a hope."></div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q-btn" type="button">
              <span>Is it safe to buy a hardware wallet from Amazon or eBay?</span>
              <span class="faq-arrow">&rsaquo;</span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-bubble-wrap">
              <div class="faq-bubble" data-text="Buying from third-party sellers introduces supply chain risk. Devices could be intercepted, opened, pre-loaded with a seed phrase the attacker knows, and repackaged convincingly. Multiple documented cases exist of this exact attack. Always purchase directly from the manufacturer's official website. When the device arrives, verify packaging integrity, check that the device initializes as new (not pre-configured), and run the manufacturer's authenticity verification."></div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q-btn" type="button">
              <span>What happens to my crypto if I die?</span>
              <span class="faq-arrow">&rsaquo;</span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-bubble-wrap">
              <div class="faq-bubble" data-text="Without an inheritance plan, your crypto is likely lost forever. Unlike bank accounts, there is no institution that can grant your heirs access. You need to create a documented recovery plan: a sealed letter of instruction stored with your will, explaining where your seed backups are located and how to use them. For advanced setups, consider multi-sig with a trusted family member or lawyer as cosigner, or Shamir's Secret Sharing (SLIP39) with shares distributed among trusted parties."></div>
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

